Observers are capable of making rapid and accurate judgments
of the average information in an array of multiple elements.
To which extent this is achieved through serial or parallel mechanisms
is still a matter of discussion.
Summary statistics propose an efficient way of extracting information from perception.
This experimental and computational study brings evidence towards a parallel extraction of
average information in human visual perception.
Items are colored shapes between squares and circles ('squircles').
Participants need to report the category (square / circle), or the estimation of the average.
Relevant dimension was shape, or an interaction between shape and color.
